            <p class="section__label">Origins</p>
            <h2 class="section__title">Child of the Siberian ice</h2>
            <div class="article-body">
              <p>The Siberian Husky is one of the oldest breeds in the world. It was developed by the Chukchi people of northeastern Siberia more than 3,000 years ago. Its role: pull sleds over vast distances in temperatures of –60°C, while living in packs inside the family yurts at night.</p>
              <p>It is this close cohabitation with humans over millennia that explains the breed's gentle, non-dominant temperament — contrary to what its wolf-like appearance might suggest. A Husky is not a guard dog. It is a partner.</p>
              <div class="tip-box"><strong>Legendary feat:</strong> In 1925, teams of Huskies covered 1,000 km in 5 days to deliver a diphtheria serum to Nome, Alaska. The lead dog Balto is immortalised in a statue in Central Park.</div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div style="margin-top:4rem" class="reveal">
          <div class="article-body" style="max-width:100%">
            <h2>A dog made for the active family</h2>
            <p>The Husky is a born athlete. It needs a minimum of two hours of exercise per day — a non-negotiable requirement. In return, you will have a companion of absolute loyalty, gentle with children, sociable with other dogs, and strikingly beautiful.</p>
            <h3>The bicolour gaze</h3>
            <p>The Husky's eyes are perhaps its most striking feature. Blue, brown, green, or heterochromia (one of each) — every Husky carries a unique gaze. Genetically, this variety is linked to a mutation in the ALX4 gene, which affects pigment concentration in the iris.</p>
